# Cloudflare Pages Cache-Control policy for the static export.
# https://developers.cloudflare.com/pages/configuration/headers/
#
# Without this file the site relies on the host's default caching, which both
# re-fetches content-hashed immutable assets and risks serving stale HTML.
#
# Cloudflare applies *every* matching rule and joins a repeated header with a
# comma, so two rules that both match a path and both set Cache-Control would
# emit one conflicting value. Rules are processed top-to-bottom, and a later,
# more specific rule can detach an inherited header with `! <Header>`. So the
# broad revalidate rule comes first, and each more specific rule below detaches
# that inherited Cache-Control before setting its own — leaving each path with
# a single, unambiguous value instead of several comma-joined ones.

# Baseline security headers, applied site-wide. More specific rules below only
# detach/reset Cache-Control (`! Cache-Control`), so these keep applying to
# every path — including hashed assets and metadata routes — without repeating
# them per rule.
#
# - Content-Security-Policy: no 'unsafe-inline' needed for script-src. The
#   JSON-LD <script> (JsonLdScript.tsx) is inline, but it's typed
#   `application/ld+json` — per the HTML spec, a <script> element only executes
#   (and only counts as a "script" for CSP's script-src) when its type is empty,
#   a JavaScript MIME type, or "module"; a non-JS type like this is just an inert
#   data block the parser never runs, CSP or not. Every actual script/style/font
#   is self-hosted under content-hashed /_next/static/* URLs (next/font resolves
#   Geist at build time, no runtime Google Fonts request), there are no <form>s,
#   and nothing on the page issues fetch/XHR calls — so every fetch directive
#   below can stay locked to 'self' or 'none' with no allowance carved out.
# - X-Content-Type-Options: stops a browser from MIME-sniffing a response into
#   an executable type against the served Content-Type.
# - Referrer-Policy: sends the full referrer to same-origin requests but only
#   the origin (no path/query) cross-origin, so outbound links don't leak this
#   site's full URL to third parties.
# - X-Frame-Options: DENY — the site never needs to be framed, so refuse
#   clickjacking-style embedding outright.
# - Permissions-Policy: the site doesn't use these browser APIs; disabling
#   them denies a compromised third-party script silent access.
# - Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy: same-origin — isolates this document's
#   top-level browsing context from any cross-origin window it opens or is
#   opened by, so a malicious cross-origin popup can't hold a `window.opener`
#   reference back into this page and can't share a process/agent-cluster
#   with it (a baseline Spectre-class side-channel mitigation). Every
#   outbound link already goes through ExternalLink.tsx's `rel="noopener
#   noreferrer"`, so this adds no new restriction on this site's own
#   behavior — it only removes the same access from third parties.
#   Deliberately not pairing this with Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy: this
#   site's own SVG (public/loop-animation.svg) is intentionally hotlinked
#   cross-origin from READMEs (see AGENTS.md), which a site-wide CORP rule
#   would block.
# - Strict-Transport-Security: moadim.io is only ever served over HTTPS (see
#   the www/.pages.dev -> apex redirects in public/_redirects), but without
#   this header a visitor's first request to a bare `http://` link or typed
#   URL still round-trips in plaintext before Cloudflare's edge can apply
#   that redirect, leaving a window for a network attacker to intercept or
#   downgrade it. `max-age=63072000` (2 years) + `includeSubDomains` +
#   `preload` meets the https://hstspreload.org submission requirements —
#   the browser only honors `preload` for domains actually baked into its
#   shipped list, so carrying the directive ahead of submission is inert,
#   not premature. Submitting the domain to the list is a separate, manual
#   opt-in step outside this repo.

# HTML and everything else: cache but always revalidate, so a redeploy is
# picked up immediately instead of serving a stale page.
/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self'; style-src 'self'; img-src 'self'; font-src 'self'; connect-src 'self'; object-src 'none'; base-uri 'none'; form-action 'none'; frame-ancestors 'none'; upgrade-insecure-requests
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
  Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin
  X-Frame-Options: DENY
  Permissions-Policy: geolocation=(), camera=(), microphone=()
  Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy: same-origin
  Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload

# Next.js emits content-hashed, immutable assets (JS, CSS, fonts, media) under
# /_next/static/*. A new build changes the hash (and the URL), so these can be
# cached forever. Detach the inherited revalidate value from the rule above so
# this path is served with the immutable directive only.
/_next/static/*
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

# Generated metadata assets whose referencing URL carries a content hash:
# the OG/Twitter share images (`/opengraph-image?<hash>`, `/twitter-image?<hash>`),
# the apple touch icon (`/apple-icon?<hash>`), and the favicon (`/icon.svg?<hash>`,
# from `app/icon.svg` — the `<link rel="icon">` href Next.js emits always
# carries a cache-busting query string). Because the URL changes whenever the
# bytes change, the bytes at any given URL are immutable — so a browser or
# crawler can cache them forever instead of re-fetching from the origin on every
# request. Without this they fall under the broad `max-age=0` rule above.
#
# The OG/Twitter/apple-icon routes also need an explicit Content-Type: the
# static export writes them as extensionless files (`out/opengraph-image`, not
# `opengraph-image.png`), so a host that infers MIME type from the file
# extension serves them as application/octet-stream instead of the image/png
# each route.tsx declares via `contentType`, breaking OG/Twitter unfurls and
# the iOS home-screen icon. `/icon.svg` ships as a real `.svg` file, so its
# type is inferred correctly without an override.
/opengraph-image
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
  Content-Type: image/png
/twitter-image
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
  Content-Type: image/png
/apple-icon
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
  Content-Type: image/png
/icon.svg
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

# Crawler-fetched metadata served from a stable, unhashed URL: robots.txt, the
# sitemap, and llms.txt (the AI-agent discovery file). These can change on a
# redeploy, so they can't be immutable — but a one-day cache still spares the
# origin a re-fetch on every crawl while letting a redeploy propagate within 24h.
/robots.txt
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400
/sitemap.xml
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400
/llms.txt
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400

